The two great facts in his life permanently im- portant are his love for his brother, and his passion for Lesbia, in whom we can hardly fail to recognise the fascinating but abandoned Clodia, the sister of Cicero’s enemy P. Clodius Pulcher, who has been held up to eternal infamy in the Pro Caelio. These were the sources that inspired much of his best work. Of his brother’s early death he writes with a genuine sorrow that still touches the deepest chords of human feeling. In the poems to Lesbia he sings at first of the complete happiness of requited love, in verse that is unsurpassed in the lover's Golden Treasury for simplicity and passion.
